{
  "texts": [
    "Stimulation can target either the peripheral or central nervous systems, but with fundamental differences in the information processing, and limitations imposed by the anatomy and physiology of the site 132.",
    "Peripheral stimulation includes stimulation of primary afferent neurons in the residual limb 39, 133 and of the DRG 134.",
    "Targeting primary afferents and the DRG has the advantage of utilizing the distinct behavior of the various receptor types to directly generate complex stimulation patterns.",
    "However, since the somatotopy is not guaranteed within nerves, the specific location of the different fibers is unknown a-priori.",
    "Thus, very selective interfaces and a long phase of mapping are required for effective targeting of the PNS."
  ]
}